statement:
Consider the differential equation system

\begin{align*}\mathbf{y}'=A\mathbf{y}\end{align*}

where A has eigenvalues $\lambda_1=-1$ and $\lambda_2=-2$ with
corresponding eigenvectors

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{k}_1&=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix},\qquad
\mathbf{k}_2&=
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Find the solution that matches the initial conditions

\begin{align*}\mathbf{y}(0)=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

hints:
How can we use our solution from
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH152/April_2011/Question_B2_(a)}{part(a)}
and the initial conditions to find the true particular solution?
